 <sect1 xml:id="sec.modules.what">
  <title>Modules &amp; Extensions Explained</title>
  <para>
   Starting with &productname; 15, the installation medium only consists of the
   &leanos;, a minimal, command line-based system for installing, updating and
   registering &productname;. During the installation you can add functionality
   by selecting modules and extensions to be installed on top of the &leanos;.
  </para>
  <para>
   Technically modules and extensions are handled similarly, they differ
   fundamentally:
  </para>
  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>Modules</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Modules are components which allow you to shape the product according to
      your needs. ach module has a clearly defined scope ranging from tools for
      Web Development and Scripting, through a Public Cloud, all the way to the
      SUSE Package Hub, offering community-managed packages. They give you the
      ability to provide just the set of packages that is required for the
      machine's purpose, making the system lean, fast, and more secure. This
      modular approach also makes it easy to provide tailor-made images for
      container and cloud environments.
     </para>
     <para>
      Technically, each module adds a set of online repositories (main, update,
      source, debug) containing packages serving a special purpose, for example
      providing development tools. In addition to that, modules may add
      partitioning proposals and system roles which can be chosen during the
      installation.  They can be added or removed at any time
      during the life cycle of the system, allowing you to easily adjust the
      system to changing requirements. &yast; or the command line tool
      <command>SUSEConnect</command> provide management tools for modules.
     </para>
     <para>
      Modules are part of your &productname; subscription and therefore free of
      charge. They differ from the base of SUSE Linux Enterprise Server only by
      their life cycle. With the exception of the SUSE Package Hub module,
      &suse; provides L3 support for almost all packages rovided by modules
      (refer to the <link
      xlink:href="https://www.suse.com/releasenotes/x86_64/SUSE-SLES/15/#Intro.Support">Release
      Notes</link>.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>Extensions</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Extensions provide advanced capabilities for tasks such as real time
      computing and high availability clustering to &productname;. They are
      offered as subscriptions and require a registration key that is liable
      for costs. Usually, extensions have their own release notes documents that
      are available from <link
      xlink:href="https://www.suse.com/releasenotes"/>.^
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>

